Pregnancy Test - Pregnancy test (H&E) can be used to determine if you are pregnant, but it is not considered a reliable pregnancy test. This test does not use antibodies against the fetus. To use a pregnancy test, you must have your menstrual cycle and the sperm in your semen tested with an assay that is appropriate for your particular situation. The following pregnancy tests work well: FSH \/ \/ + Estradiol \/ + TPO; LH \/ \/ \/ TPO \/ + mIU/ml; FSH \/ \/ \/ Estradiol \/ \/ \/ TPO; IUI \/ \/ \/ Estradiol \/ \/ \/ TPO;

If you do get pregnant using this method, and after two cycles of use, you feel the need for another one, you should start with a low dose of estrogen plus progestin (usually 10 mg every other day), followed by a higher dose of estradiol plus progesterone (4-8 pills per day). If you stop taking these medications, or if they become ineffective because you cannot tolerate them, then take the lowest effective dose until you find another way to prevent conception. Some women experience difficulty stopping birth control pills from working at all. As a result, some doctors recommend starting a new contraceptive regimen before having sex. In addition, many people who want to become pregnant may not be able to conceive unless they start using oral contraceptives immediately after their last period. When taking a combined oral contraceptive pill such as ethinyloestradiol and norethindrone acetate, do not take more than 3 days between periods. You will increase your risk of unplanned pregnancies. Use an additional form of contraception until you can safely use the combined oral contraceptive pill again without any side effects.
